Review: This movie is amazingly directed, paced rly well and every shot is a picture.
Maybe I just didnt get it? it was v mid for me, and I found myself thinking more about the ethics of the science I am watching, and was less beholden to any character development here.

William Friedkin's Sorcerer (1977) pales in comparison to this movie. Just when you think entropy has reached its peak, things literally just become exponentially more chaotic in ways i would not have imagined. This movie is dread and despair and tension and chaos and anxiety in a high pressure life or death situation.
I didn't care for this movie when Joe put it on, but whoaaaa.... surprisingly enjoyable! I think it's the kids that makes this movie a bona fide homerun 😜

WOW The early 90s rly wanted to 1-up the 80s on sarcasm and wit. Doesn't disappoint, but I felt like I was missing the "good 'ol American pasttime" vibe. Dottie's character arc was a bit disappointing tho. :(

This movie deserves to be seen again, but this first round, I was v unamused? Yorgos explored some themes in life, identity and sexuality that I never would've expected would make it to the big screen.... but ahhhhh so refreshing to see this! It was too serious and too introspective that seeing Anyone But You first rly made me exhausted after seeing this.
Had no idea that Glen Powell was hot, but this movie changed my mind. Tbf, he's topless for almost half the film 😮‍💨 Women stood no chance.

Needed to reflect on this one for a while bc the themes are definitely not novel but it encouraged me to think about why I do what I do, my own pursuit of greatness and what am I willing to give up to achieve this ~greatness~Honestly, older movies are so much more fun and unpredictable than the more recent films, bc I had absolutely no idea where the movie would take me next each time each character makes a…

if anyone ever decides to want to wallow in self-pity and pathetic energy, this one would be the first to watch. Jesus, this movie makes Requiem for a Dream a fucking party. It’s sorrow without catharsis, loneliness without being alone, agony without any hint of joy. I’m never watching this movie again. Fuckin hell.
C-list horror movies will always have a special place in my heart. 🦝 and if we’re being honest I rly did get got. Has anyone here seen Michael Douglas’ The Game?
I thought this was supposed to feel like Whiplash or Black Swan. Quite the opposite, she wanted personal connections and when it seemed like she’s lost it all, not even “work” can fill the holes.
